    <stitle>DT 466 / DT 570 / HT 570 Diesel Engine Diagnostic Manual - 2004 Emissions with EGR - Engine Systems - Air
        Management System - Charge Air Cooler (CAC)
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="1">
        <title>Charge Air Cooler (CAC)</title>
        <figure id="f2700113" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figD15/D1530.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Charge Air Cooler (typical)</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Air outlet</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Charge Air Cooler (CAC)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Air inlet</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Radiator</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <para>The CAC is mounted on top of the radiator. Air from the turbocharger passes through a network of heat
            exchanger tubes before entering the EGR mixer duct. Outside air flowing over the tubes and fins cools the
            charged air. Charged air is cooler and denser than the uncooled air; cooler and denser air improves the
            fuel-to-air ratio during combustion, resulting in improved emission control and power output.
        </para>
    </svcproc>
